"'''Talk That Talk'''" is a song recorded by Barbadian singer [[Rihanna]] for her 2011 [[Talk That Talk (Rihanna album)|studio album of the same name]]. It features a [[Rapping|rap verse]] by American [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] artist [[Jay Z]], who had previously collaborated with Rihanna on her song "[[Umbrella (song)|Umbrella]]" in 2007 and "[[Run This Town]]" in 2009. The song was written by [[Ester Dean]], [[Shawn Carter]], [[The Notorious B.I.G.|Christopher Wallace]], [[Buckwild|Anthony Best]], [[Sean Combs]], and [[Chucky Thompson]] together with the Norwegian production duo [[Stargate (production team)|StarGate]]. [[Def Jam Recordings]] serviced the track to [[urban radio]] in the United States on January 17, 2012, as the third single from ''Talk That Talk''. It was released in France as a [[CD single]] on March 26. "Talk That Talk" is a hip hop song with [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] beats, rough drums and unrefined [[Synthesizer|synths]], and has a similar style to Rihanna's 2010 single "[[Rude Boy (song)|Rude Boy]]".

The single received generally positive reviews from critics, who praised its sound and Rihanna's collaboration with Jay Z. It was nominated for a [[Grammy Award for Best Rap/Sung Collaboration]] at the [[2013 Grammy Awards|2013 ceremony]]. The song appeared on several charts worldwide; it reached number 31 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], number 25 on the [[UK Singles Chart]], and the top ten in Israel, Norway, and South Korea. It was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), denoting digital downloads of over 500,000 copies in the US. Rihanna performed "Talk That Talk" on television shows such as ''[[The Jonathan Ross Show]]'' and ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', and included it on the [[set list]] of her 2013 tour, the [[Diamonds World Tour]].

==Background==
[[File:Jay-Z-02-mika.jpg|left|thumb|upright|alt=A black-and-white picture of an African-American man wearing a white shirt, trousers, a cap and a wristwatch.|"Talk That Talk" features rapper [[Jay Z]], who also co-wrote the song.]]

Before her sixth studio album ''[[Talk That Talk]]'' was released in November 2011, Rihanna announced on her [[Twitter]] account that, apart from the song "[[We Found Love]]" with [[Calvin Harris]], the album would have only one other featured artist, although she did not mention the artist's name.<ref name="RapUp1">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2011/11/07/jay-z-reunites-with-rihanna-on-talk-that-talk/#more-103469|title=Jay-Z Reunites with Rihanna on 'Talk That Talk'|work=[[Rap-Up]]|date=November 7, 2011|accessdate=November 14, 2011}}</ref> Jay Brown, Rihanna's manager, explained that they preferred to record independently rather than collaborate with other artists.<ref name="Spy">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/thesound/a350264/rihannas-new-album-talk-that-talk-first-listen.html|title=Rihanna's new album 'Talk That Talk': First listen|publisher= [[Digital Spy]]|last=Copsey|first=Robert|date=November 10, 2011|accessdate=November 14, 2011}}</ref> On November 8, Rihanna confirmed on Twitter that her mentor, the American rapper [[Jay Z]], would appear as a featured artist on the album's title track.<ref name="MTV1">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1673976/rihanna-jay-z-talk-that-talk.jhtml|title=Rihanna Confirms Jay-Z Talk That Talk Cameo|publisher= [[MTV News]]|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|date=November 8, 2011|accessdate=November 14, 2011}}</ref> Brown said that the collaboration "happened organically".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/rihanna/337117-rihanna-talk-that-talk-first-listen-jay-z-calvin-harris|title=Rihanna <U+2013> 'Talk That Talk' First Listen! |publisher= [[MTV UK]]|last=Dorken|first=Joanne|date=November 10, 2011|accessdate=November 16, 2011}}</ref>

"Talk That Talk" is the third major collaboration between Rihanna and Jay Z, who had worked together on "[[Umbrella (song)|Umbrella]]" in 2007 and "[[Run This Town]]" in 2009.<ref name= "MTV1"/> "Umbrella" was the lead single from Rihanna's 2007 album ''[[Good Girl Gone Bad (Rihanna album)|Good Girl Gone Bad]]'' and topped the charts in more than ten countries, including the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], on which it spent seven consecutive weeks at number one.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1050760/plain-white-ts-finally-unseats-rihanna-on-hot-100|title=Plain White T's Finally Unseats Rihanna On Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate= November 14, 2011}}</ref> "Run This Town", which also featured rapper [[Kanye West]], was released as the second single from Jay Z's 2009 album ''[[The Blueprint 3]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1616871/20090724/jay_z.jhtml|title=Jay-Z's 'Run This Town' Makes Radio Debut|publisher=MTV News|last=Reid|first=Shaheem|date=July 24, 2009|accessdate=November 14, 2011}}</ref>
{{clear}}

==Production and release==

"Talk That Talk" was written by [[Ester Dean]], [[Mikkel S. Eriksen]], [[Tor Erik Hermansen]], [[Shawn Carter]], [[Buckwild|Anthony Best]], [[Sean Combs]], and [[Chucky Thompson]].<ref name="Booklet"/> It was produced by Eriksen and Hermansen, who were credited under their production name [[Stargate (production team)|StarGate]].<ref name="Booklet"/> They had produced Rihanna's 2010 hit singles "[[Only Girl (In the World)]]" and "[[What's My Name? (Rihanna song)|What's My Name?]]" for her fifth album ''[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]''.<ref>{{Cite music release notes |title=''[[Loud (Rihanna album)|Loud]]'' |Type=album |Artist=[[Rihanna]] |Year=2010 |Format=liner notes |Publisher=Def Jam, SRP}}</ref> In an interview for the Norwegian website 730.no, Hermansen revealed that it was first time they had collaborated with Jay Z and said that they were very satisfied with both the song and each artist's contribution.<ref name="RapUp1"/> "Talk That Talk" was recorded at Roc the Mic Studios and The Jungle City Studios in New York City, [[Westlake Recording Studios]] in Los Angeles, and The Hide Out Studios in London. Eriksen, Miles Walker, and Mike Anderson served as the song's [[Audio engineer|recording engineer]]s. Rihanna's vocals were recorded by Marcos Tovar and [[Kuk Harrell]], who additionally produced them, while Jordan "DJ Swivel" Young recorded Jay Z's verses. Additional recording of the song was done in Sofitel Paris Le Faubourg and [[Savoy Hotel|Savoy London]] hotels. "Talk That Talk" was [[Mixing (music production)|mixed]] by [[Phil Tan]] and assistant Daniela Rivera at Ninja Beat Club Studios in [[Atlanta]]. Eriksen and Hermansen recorded the song's instrumentation, and Tim Blacksmith and Danny D. were assigned as its [[executive producer]]s.<ref name="Booklet"/>

In December 2011, Rihanna asked her fans on Twitter to recommend a song from ''Talk That Talk'' for release as the third single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/rihanna/news/talk-talk-single-single/|title=Rihanna Unveils 'Talk That Talk' Single Artwork|publisher=[[Capital (radio network)|Capital FM]]|date=January 11, 2012|accessdate=January 20, 2012}}</ref> On January 10, 2012, she announced that the title track was chosen<ref name="single announced">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/513327/rihanna-reveals-next-single-talk-that-talk|title=Rihanna Reveals Next Single: 'Talk That Talk'|work=Billboard|date=January 11, 2012|accessdate=January 11, 2012}}</ref> and also debuted the single's cover<U+2014>a black-and-white image in which Rihanna is dressed in "street punk/rockabilly clothes" and crouches against a wall.<ref name="single announced"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1677082/rihanna-talk-that-talk-single.jhtml|title=Rihanna Reveals Next Talk That Talk Single|publisher=MTV News|date=January 11, 2012|accessdate=January 20, 2012}}</ref> According to Jazmine Gray of ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' magazine, the singer's has an ambiguous facial expression on the cover.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/rihanna-shows-talk-talk-single-artwork|title=Rihanna Shows Off 'Talk That Talk' Single Artwork|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|last=Gray|first=Jazmine|date=January 11, 2012|accessdate=September 18, 2013}}</ref> On January 17, [[Def Jam Recordings]] serviced "Talk That Talk" to [[urban contemporary]] radio stations in the United States.<ref name="radio">{{cite web|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=01/17/2012&Format=5|title=R&R :: Going for Adds :: Urban|publisher=[[Radio and Records]]|accessdate=January 22, 2012}}</ref> It also impacted US [[contemporary hit radio|contemporary hit]] and [[Rhythmic contemporary|rhythmic]] radios on February 14.<ref name="gfa.radioandrecords.com">{{cite web|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=02/14/2012&Format=1|title=R&R :: Going for Adds :: CHR/Top 40|publisher=Radio and Records|accessdate=January 22, 2012}}</ref><ref name="gfa.radioandrecords">{{cite web|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=02/14/2012&Format=9|title=R&R :: Going for Adds :: Rhythmic|publisher=Radio and Records|accessdate=January 22, 2012}}</ref> On March 26, "Talk That Talk" was released in France as a [[CD single]], which contained the album version of the song and the Chuckie Extended Remix of "We Found Love".<ref name="cd single"/>

==Composition and lyrical interpretation==
{{listen|filename=Rihanna - Talk That Talk.ogg|title="Talk That Talk"
|description=A sample of "Talk That Talk", a [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] song with a [[Pop music|pop]] [[Hook (music)|hook]] that features [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] [[Beat (music)|beats]], rough drums, unrefined [[synths]], and a [[sampling (music)|sample]] of the song "I Got a Story to Tell" by rapper [[The Notorious B.I.G.]].
|pos=right
|format=[[Ogg]]}}

"Talk That Talk" has a length of three minutes and twenty-nine seconds.<ref name="itunes">{{cite web|url=http://itunes.apple.com/us/album/talk-that-talk-deluxe-edition/id479321646|title=Rihanna <U+2013> Talk That Talk (Deluxe Edition)|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] (US). [[Apple Inc]]|accessdate=March 26, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's Claire Suddath characterized it as a lively [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] track with a [[Pop music|pop]] [[Hook (music)|hook]].<ref name="Time">{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2011/11/21/music-monday-rihannas-talk-that-talk/|title=Album Review: Rihanna's Talk That Talk|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|last=Suddath|first=Claire|date=November 21, 2011|accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref> It features [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] [[Beat (music)|beats]],<ref name="digital spy">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/singlesreviews/a370952/rihanna-ft-jay-z-talk-that-talk-single-review.html|title=Rihanna ft. Jay-Z: 'Talk That Talk' <U+2013> Single review|publisher=Digital Spy|last=Corner|first=Lewis|date=March 13, 2012|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref> "hard drums", unrefined [[synths]],<ref name="RapUp1"/> and a [[sampling (music)|sample]] of the song "I Got a Story to Tell" by rapper [[The Notorious B.I.G.]].<ref name="Spy"/>

Adrian Thrills from the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' described the song as "slow and sultry".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/reviews/article-2063019/Rihanna-Talk-That-Talk-music-review-RnB-queen-says-loud.html|title=It seems even pop's most provocative princess is a romantic at heart... Rihanna reveals she just wants love|work=[[Daily Mail]]|last=Thrills|first=Adrian|date=November 18, 2011|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> Similarly, Sam Lansky of [[MTV Buzzworthy]] found it sensual and confident, and observed that Rihanna counts when she sings the song's [[Refrain|chorus]].<ref name="buzzworthy">{{cite web|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2011/11/21/rihanna-talk-that-talk/|title=Rihanna's 'Talk That Talk': A Track-By-Track Guide To Her New Album|publisher=[[MTV Buzzworthy]]|last=Lansky|first=Sam|date=November 21, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref> [[IGN]]'s Chad Grischow wrote that a "fuzzy synth melody" interjects Rihanna's "sexy plea for pillow talk", which is complemented by "bling-loving rap from Jay Z."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2011/11/22/rihanna-talk-that-talk-review|title=Rihanna: Talk That Talk Review|publisher=[[IGN]]|last=Grischow|first=Chad|date=November 22, 2011|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref> [[Digital Spy]]'s Robert Copsey felt that its [[Riff (music)|riff]] is similar to Rihanna's 2010 single "[[Rude Boy (song)|Rude Boy]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/albumreviews/a351462/rihanna-talk-that-talk-album-review.html|title=Rihanna: 'Talk That Talk' <U+2013> Album review|publisher=Digital Spy|last=Copsey|first=Robert|date=November 21, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref>

The song begins with a rap verse performed by Jay Z, whose lines include: "I talk big money, I talk big homes / I sell out arenas, I call that getting dome / Million dollar voice, came through phone / We heading to the top, if you coming, come on".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/11/13/rihanna-talk-that-talk-new-song-with-jay-z/|title=Rihanna Drops 'Talk That Talk' Single Featuring Jay-Z|publisher=MTV News|last= D.L.|first=Chandler|date=November 13, 2011|accessdate=November 14, 2011}}</ref> He raps at a slow pace and incorporates both [[double entendre]]s and humorous remarks, including a sexual reference that Claire Suddath viewed was an indication of Jay Z's enjoyment on the song: "[I] had it by her bladder, she's like 'Oh I gotta pee!'."<ref name="Time"/> Melissa Maerz from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' remarked that he "even touts their jet-set lifestyle on the title track, bragging that he can fly out to Pisa / Just to get some pizza."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20545856,00.html|title= Talk That Talk review <U+2013> Rihanna review|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Maerz|first=Melissa|date=November 16, 2011|accessdate=November 17, 2011}}</ref>

==Critical reception==
[[File:Grammy.jpg|thumb|left|upright|alt=A gold gramophone trophy with a plaque set on a table|"Talk That Talk" received a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Rap/Sung Collaboration|Best Rap/Sung Collaboration]]]]

"Talk That Talk" was well received by most [[Music journalism|music critics]]. ''[[Daily Mirror]]''{{'}}s Gavin Martin commented that the song has Rihanna "stealing not just [[Beyonc<U+00E9> Knowles|Beyonc<U+00E9>]]'s bootylicious crown but also her husband Jay Z for a frisky exchange against sibilant drum cracks."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/columnists/gavin-martin/2011/11/18/rihanna-talk-that-talk-album-review-ri-ri-drops-a-sex-bomb-115875-23566404/|title=Rihanna Talk That Talk album review: Ri-Ri drops a sex bomb|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|last=Martin|first=Gavin|date=November 18, 2011|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> [[Sputnikmusic]]'s Steve M. felt that it could be a major hit on radio partly because of Jay Z's guest rap.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sputnikmusic.com/review/46572/Rihanna-Talk-That-Talk/|title=Rihanna Talk That Talk|publisher=[[Sputnik Music]]|last=M|first=Steve|date=November 17, 2011|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> Reem Buhazza of ''[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]'' similarly felt that "Talk That Talk", along with "[[You da One]]" and "[[Roc Me Out]]", is part of "the winning combination of made-for-radio pop sensibility".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/music/rihanna-talk-that-talk|title=Rihanna: Talk That Talk|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|last=Buhazza|first=Reem|date=November 22, 2011|accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> David Griffiths from [[4Music]] found the song to be compelling and viewed it as another successful collaboration between Rihanna and Jay Z.<ref name="4MUSIC">{{cite web|url=http://www.4music.com/news/reviews/1992/Rihanna-Talk-That-Talk|title=News: Talk That Talk|publisher= [[4Music]]|last=Griffiths|first=David|date=November 10, 2011|accessdate= November 18, 2011}}</ref> Lansky from MTV Buzzworthy was not surprised that another collaboration between the two was a success.<ref name="buzzworthy"/> [[MTV News]]{{'}} Jocelyn Vena called it "big and hard with just enough brightness" and felt that the song discusses [[sexual intercourse]] more appropriately than "[[Cockiness (Love It)]]";<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1674711/rihanna-talk-that-talk-tracks.jhtml|title=Rihanna's Talk That Talk: Five Key Tracks|publisher= MTV News|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|date=November 21, 2011|accessdate=November 23, 2011}}</ref> in the latter, Rihanna expresses her desire to have sex while singing the lyrics "Suck my cockiness, lick my persuasion".<ref>{{cite news|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/465081/rihanna-talk-that-talk-track-by-track-review|title=Rihanna, 'Talk That Talk': Track-By-Track Review|work=Billboard|date=November 17, 2011|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref>

Lewis Corner of Digital Spy gave the song four out of five stars and called it an enticing, anthemic club song.<ref name="digital spy"/> In a review of ''Talk That Talk'', [[Pitchfork Media]]'s Lindsay Zoladz wrote that it is one of the album's more lighthearted songs, even though it is not as good as "Umbrella".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/16072-rihanna-talk-that-talk/|title=Rihanna: Talk That Talk|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]]|last=Zoladz|first=Lindsay|date=November 23, 2011|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref> [[Consequence of Sound]]'s Chris Coplan found Jay Z's rap unenthusiastic, but said that Rihanna is as emotional and invested in her singing as she was on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2011/11/album-review-rihanna-talk-that-talk/|title=Album Review: Rihanna <U+2013> Talk That Talk|publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Coplan|first=Chris|date=November 22, 2011|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref> ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine's Chuck Arnold called the song "another moment in the sun."<ref name="people magazine">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20547520,00.html|title=Rihanna: Talk That Talk Review by People music critic|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|last=Arnold|first=Chuck|date=November 21, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref> Julianne Escobedo Shepherd of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' thought that it is a collaboration that "does not go unnoticed".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/rihanna-talk-talk-def-jam/|title=Rihanna, 'Talk That Talk' Review|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|last=Shepherd|first=Julianne Escobedo|date=November 21, 2011|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref> On the critical side, Priya Elan of ''[[NME]]'' wrote that the song is a "gamble that doesn<U+2019>t pay off".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/rihanna/12476|title=NME Album Reviews <U+2013> Album Review: Rihanna <U+2013> 'Talk That Talk'|work=[[NME]]|last=Elan|first=Priya|date=November 18, 2011|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref> The single was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Rap/Sung Collaboration|Best Rap/Sung Collaboration]] at the [[2013 Grammy Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a443317/grammy-awards-2013-the-major-nominees.html|title=Grammy Awards 2013: The major nominees|publisher=Digital Spy|last=Goodacre|first=Kate|date=December 6, 2012|accessdate=December 12, 2012}}</ref> but lost to "[[No Church in the Wild]]" (2012) by Jay Z and Kanye West featuring [[Frank Ocean]] and [[The-Dream]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2013/02/grammy-winners-2013-full-list/|title=Grammy Winners 2013: Full List|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=February 11, 2013|accessdate=August 20, 2013}}</ref>
{{clear}}

==Chart performance==

After the release of the album, the song charted in many countries owing to strong digital sales. It debuted and peaked at number 31 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and sold 73,000 digital copies, which was the highest debut on the chart for that week.<ref name="US debut"/> In the week of February 4, 2012, "Talk That Talk" re-entered the chart at number 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2012-02-04/the-hot-100?order=gainer|title=The Hot 100: Feb 04, 2012 (Biggest Jump)|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref> It reached number 36 in the week of March 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2012-02-04/the-hot-100?order=gainer|title=The Hot 100: Mar 24, 2012 <U+2013> (Biggest Jump)|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref> The song also appeared on the [[R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] chart at number 63 in the issue dated January 28.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2012-01-28/r-b-hip-hop-songs?order=gainer|title=Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs: Jan 28, 2012 <U+2013> (Biggest Jump)|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 21, 2013}}</ref> It peaked of number 12 and stayed on the chart for 21 weeks.<ref name="US R&B"/> It was ranked number 73 on the [[Billboard Year-End|''Billboard''{{'}}s year-end]] R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart.<ref name="year end chart"/> On the [[Pop Songs]] chart, the single debuted and peaked at number 26 in the week of April 7.<ref name="pop"/> It was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), denoting digital downloads of 500,000 copies in the United States.<ref name="riaa">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?artist=Rihanna|title=Searchable database|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=August 31, 2012}}</ref> "Talk That Talk" debuted and peaked at number 30 on the [[Canadian Hot 100]] chart.<ref name="Canada and Japan"/>

In Europe, after the release of the album, the song appeared on ten national charts. In the United Kingdom, it debuted at number 25 on the [[UK Singles Chart|Singles Chart]],<ref name="UK"/> and reached number seven on the [[UK R&B Chart|R&B Chart]].<ref name="UK R&B"/> The song made a top-ten debut on the [[VG-lista|Norwegian Singles Chart]] and charted at number 11 on the [[Swiss Hitparade|Swiss Singles Chart]].<ref name="NOR"/> It also made top-forty appearances in the Republic of Ireland,<ref name="IRE"/> New Zealand,<ref name="NZ"/> and Spain, and also entered the top thirty in Scotland,<ref name="SCO"/> France,<ref name="FRA"/> and Denmark.<ref name="DEN"/> After its release as a single, "Talk That Talk" entered the [[ARIA Charts|Australian Singles Chart]] at number 42 and peaked at number 28 on February 19.<ref name="AUS"/> It was certified gold by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) for selling 35,000 digital copies.<ref name="ausgold"/> Following the release of the album, the song debuted in South Korea on the [[Gaon Chart|Gaon International Chart]] at number 22 with sales of 14,207 digital copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/digital_chart/download.php?nationGbn=E&current_week=49&current_year=2011&chart_Time=week|title=South Korea Gaon International Chart (Week: November 20, 2011 to November 26, 2011)|publisher=[[Gaon Chart]]|accessdate=August 21, 2013}}</ref> The following week, it sold 27,169 more copies and peaked at number 9 on the chart.<ref name="korea"/>

==Live performances==
[[File:Rihanna Diamonds World Tour 7, 2013.jpg|upright|thumbnail|right|alt=A woman with blonde-brownish hair is performing while holding a gold microphone in her hands. She is wearing silky black outfit and has a golden chain on her neck.|Rihanna performing "Talk That Talk" on the [[Diamonds World Tour]] (2013)]]
Rihanna first performed "Talk That Talk" on the British talk show ''[[The Jonathan Ross Show]]'', which aired on March 3, 2012. She performed without Jay Z and was also interviewed.<ref name="Jonathan">{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/rihanna/news/talk-that-talk-live-video/|title=Rihanna Performs 'Talk That Talk' Live On Jonathan Ross Show - Video|publisher=Capital FM|date=March 4, 2012|accessdate=August 29, 2013}}</ref> On May 5, Rihanna performed the song on the American comedy show ''Saturday Night Live'' as part of a medley that included the original interlude version of "[[Birthday Cake (song)|Birthday Cake]]".<ref name="SNL2012">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2012/05/05/rihanna-performs-on-snl/|title=Rihanna performs on 'SNL'|work=Rap-Up|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> In her performance, she wore an all-black outfit with a giant spider web as her backdrop.<ref name="SNL2012"/> She first sung a short section of "Birthday Cake" and transitioned into "Talk That Talk", which was performed in its entirety.<ref name="SNL2012"/> Rihanna and Jay Z performed "Talk That Talk" together at the 2012 BBC Radio 1's [[Hackney Weekend]] in London. The performance also featured their previous collaborations "Run This Town" and "Umbrella".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/18575052|title=Rihanna and Jay-Z make 'history' at R1 Hackney Weekend|publisher=[[BBC]]|last=Cochrane|first=Greg|date=June 25, 2012|accessdate=September 18, 2012}}</ref> In November, she included the song on the [[set list]] of her [[Unapologetic#777 Tour|777 Tour]], a seven-day long promotional tour that supported the release of her 2012 album ''[[Unapologetic]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ramirez|first=Erika|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/474107/rihannas-777-tour-diary-day-four-paris|title=Rihanna's 777 Tour Diary: Day Four, Paris|work=Billboard|date=November 18, 2012|accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref> "Talk That Talk" was also included on the set list of her 2013 [[Diamonds World Tour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/music/ci_22974451/setlist-rihanna-san-jose|title=Setlist: Rihanna in San Jose|publisher=[[Mercury News]]|last=Harrington|first=Jim|date=April 6, 2013|accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref>

